  "prompt": "How much native Icelandic and advanced Icelandic learners can read and understand Old Norse?",
  "response": "The ability to read and understand Old Norse varies among native Icelandic speakers and advanced learners. Generally:\n\n1. Native Icelandic speakers:\n- Most can understand some Old Norse texts with relative ease due to the close linguistic relationship\n- Many can read historical texts like the Sagas with some effort\n- Younger generations may have more difficulty compared to older generations\n\n2. Advanced Icelandic learners:\n- Highly proficient learners can often read Old Norse with some assistance\n- Comprehension typically requires specific study and training in historical linguistics\n- Understanding varies based on individual study and exposure\n\nWhile Icelandic and Old Norse are closely related, full comprehension isn't automatic and requires dedicated study. The languages are similar but not identical, with notable differences in grammar, vocabulary, and pronunciation.\n\nPrecise statistics on full comprehension are limited, but linguistic research suggests that with proper education, many Icelandic speakers can engage with Old Norse texts to some degree.",
